charity.description:
At Macmillan, we will move mountains to help people with cancer live life as fully as they can.

We’re doing whatever it takes. But without your help we can’t support everyone who needs us. To
donate, volunteer, raise money or campaign with us, call 0300 1000 200 or visit macmillan.org.uk
charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story: Macmillan Cancer Support gave my mum so much support, care and dignity and without their support my mum would not of been able to come home for her last days with us. They were also very supportive to my family too and for that I am forever grateful.

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Cancer is not going anywhere and Macmillan Cancer Support is needed now more than ever. By donating to my Run It challenge you can help to ensure that people living with cancer get the vital support they need right now.

Everyone knows someone effected by cancer, I’m no exception and in recent years, some of those closest to me have fought the fight and won! The battle is tough and often long; for many the support of charities like Macmillan is invaluable.

I usually do the Macmillan cake bake where I get to indulge in cake as well as raise money for a good cause but this time I’m looking to “run it”! Any small contribution would be much appreciated xx

Our volunteers provide first aid in their communities and thanks to them fewer lives will be lost needlessly.

charity.name: St John Ambulance
story:
Between 27 January and 31 March, we'll be virtually taking part in the Virgin Pulse step challenge. We'll be walking between Vancouver and East Australia to raise funds for St John Ambulance and their absolutely vital and much appreciated work assisting the NHS on the Covid-19 vaccine roll out.

Alicia Convery, Emma Dooley, Steve Burke, Ed Cooper, Saleem Fazal, Lesley Collins and Lorraine Frake join Taylor Wessing in raising £10,000 for St John Ambulance to support the health of our communities.

story:
Between 27 January and 31 March, we are joining hundreds of colleagues from our firm, Taylor Wessing,  in "virtually" walking/ running/ cycling/ dancing from Vancouver to Sydney, as part of the Virgin Pulse step challenge.

We're aiming to collectively raise at least £20,000 for St John Ambulance to support the health of our communities and the UK COVID-19 vaccine rollout programme.

Our team members:

  1. Louisa Boersma
  2. Lucy Brunt
  3. Claire Edwards
  4. James Langley
  5. Anna Lewington
  6. Tom "marathon man" Luong
  7. Catherine Webb

charity.name: St John Ambulance
story: As a charity with a long history of serving humanity, we are proud of our past, our role in the pandemic and excited about creating a healthier, safer, brighter and more resilient future. This winter may be our toughest yet and I am helping to bring some community spirit by sharing my sparkle by supporting St John. St John volunteers treat and transport thousands of patients each year, and in times of crisis we are England's national health reserve. During the pandemic our skilled and highly trained volunteers are working long shifts supporting sick people and their families, in hospitals, in ambulances and at home. We are proud to be working alongside the nations ambulance trusts and in hospitals around the country. "I enjoy helping people and its what I have been training to do. Its very rewarding personally knowing that my colleagues and I are making a difference to peoples lives when they most need it." Tom Willis, volunteer Will you support me and help make a difference?

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
We're collecting vital funds for the British Heart Foundation, to power pioneering research into heart and cardiovascular diseases. The money we raise will help beat heartbreak forever.

We have chosen the British Heart Foundation as our charity for 2021 in remembrance of Nicola Westcott, who sadly passed away in December 2020. Nicola's sons both played for the Club and her husband Sean has been a tremendous servant as coach, committee member, and vice-chairman. None of that would have been possible without Nicola's unwavering support.

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

story:
I’m surrounded by chocolate all day every day. As a baker it’s the best part of most cakes and bakes and I’m a big fan! 

Before covid I was a big fan of giving back to the community through my dance school but it’s been made near impossible now classes aren’t running. It’s time I hassled you all for money again - this time for the British Heart Foundation - see their little input below 😊 

I’ll find this really difficult as I’ve got a real sweet tooth and I’ll be continuing to bake all my cakes and traybakes. But after a year of focusing on my family and my new business it’s time to do something for others - please donate what you can! 

Thank you! Jenn xx

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

story:
We’ll be giving up all things chocolate for the month of March, even that little sprinkle on the top of our cappuccinos! For those of you who know us, we are MASSIVE chocoholics and so this is major for us! We’ll be raising money to help the BHF incredible research in memory of our Dad, who we lost to heart disease when we were little 💕

We’ll be donating 10% of all Millennial Menu Bakes profits in March too, so we can make this Dechox go a little further 🍫 

The pandemic is the biggest challenge the BHF has faced in their 60 year history. And it's led to them being forced to make the devastating decision to cut their 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, they’ve never needed fundraisers more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. 

So, our willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most. Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

Go on, donate even £1 to help the BHF and their amazing work 💕

Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

story:
Hello, I'm Caroline and I'm a chocoholic 🙋‍♀️ I've decided to take on the challenge of giving up chocolate,  sweets and fizzy drinks for the whole of March. Anyone who knows me knows that I'm going to find this tough, but if my fella can do dry January successfully then I can do Dechox. 


Thanks in advance to anyone who sponsors me.


Caroline xx

When I saw the DECHOC challenge for the British heart foundation I felt it was perfect for me! I was hoping you could support me with this very worthy cause, for which I will not eat anything that has any chocolate in it during March!  

As we all have been through the most, shocking, surprising, emotionally challenged, locked down year of our life ! I understand it might not be easy to support my challenge, but even the smallest amount will help! Below you can find a little bit of info about the British heart foundation! 

Stay safe!

Thank you in advance! Warmest wishes!

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation's research and I'd be so grateful for your support. As some of you may know my mum has both atrial fibrillation and hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, but thanks to the research that the BHF carry out she can be treated to manage her symptoms, and we always have access to any information we need. Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy is a genetic condition which can pass through families, but there has been a huge breakthrough last month in the testing family members of known sufferers, and together we can make even more of a difference!

charity.description: The ability to get around is vital in order to live a full life yet thousands of people with sight loss never leave home alone. We empower visually impaired people to do that and rely on the support of the public to fund the guide dog service.
charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
As a result of the latest developments, we are unable to go ahead with thousands of collections planned across the UK in the coming months. Guide Dogs remains committed to supporting people with sight loss across the UK.

It has never been more important to come together online and support one another. We appreciate times are difficult right now, but for people with sight loss, social isolation can be their every day. 

By hosting a virtual collection for Guide Dogs, every pound you or your group raises will ensure we can continue to help people with sight loss and feel less alone, now and in the future. It costs £13 a day to support each of our life changing dogs.

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Since this lockdown is driving me crazy and has me bored out my mind constantly i’ve decided that in order to tackle the boredom the right thing to do is get myself out the house and try to raise a bit of money for charity! 

Basically the aim is that by the time February ends i’ll have walked 170km which is about 6k a day! I know it doesn’t seem like much but honestly the last few weeks i’ve been the laziest wee cow and have spent about 95% of my time in bed🤣

Any money raised will go to the amazing Marie Curie charity which is an organisation that allows nurses to go the extra mile to provide care for those and the family of those suffering from terminal illnesses who need end of life care. My gran spent a short time with Marie Curie nurses before she passed and she spoke so highly of them and always appreciated how much they did for her so I think it’s time to return the favour!💛

Any donations really are appreciated because the money is going to such a great cause🌻

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
In March 2021 I am going to attempt to do 10,000 steps each day to raise money for this incredible organisation. 10,000 steps may not sound much to most people but it will be a challenge for me as I suffer with arthritis in my lower spine and both hips and I also suffer with my mental health, so there are going to be days where I am really going to have to push myself hard but I am a determined person and I like to achieve my goals.

The following is a few words from the charity..........
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel.
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk.
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Christine initially went to Marie Curie for pain management with a view to further treatment after being diagnosed with Lung Cancer in late September 2020. 

Unfortunately, her condition deteriorated rapidly and she succumbed to her illness. Her last weeks were made special thanks to the fantastic team at Marie Curie Woolton. 

Instead of flowers if any friends or family would care to make a small donation on behalf of Christine her family would be most appreciative. ❤️

At the Marie Curie Hospice, Liverpool, we give expert care to people with a terminal illness, and their loved ones every day of the year. Our hospice team includes doctors, nurses, physiotherapists, social workers and many more, and is supported by local people who freely volunteer their time and energy to help us run the hospice.As well as being a place where people can stay to get the expert care they need in a friendly and homely setting, we also support people visiting with clinics and therapies. These include yoga, exercise classes and relaxation. People using the day unit can also get together over a freshly cooked lunch from our chefs.Relatives and friends can visit any time of the day or night, and stay with their loved ones if they wish to. We need to raise £6,397 per day to run the hospice, so every penny counts. Thank you for helping to make sure more people with a terminal illness in Liverpool, get the care and support they need.

charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Our Daddy lost his battle with cancer on 11/02/20 after a few years of illness. His last time to leave his house or even his room was on 01/01/20, 42 days earlier. I decided to take on the challenge to run everyday in his memory and my mum has been walking 5 miles each day also. We plan to donate £1 per mile that we have ran/walked and would really appreciate it if others could make a small contribution as well to help us reach our target. 

Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Marie Curie nurses work night and day in peoples homes and their hospices offer specialist care. They also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.

Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Weve been caring for local people in this way for more than 50 years, now. Every single day at the hospice is an extraordinary day. 

We listen, support and give high-quality care during what can be a difficult, challenging and distressing time. And we get to know people as individuals, find out what makes them happy, and help to make those things happen.

That might mean sitting with them in the hospice garden, or arranging for their pet to visit them at the hospice. We focus on the special things that bring people joy.

We also provide important support for carers and families, including bereavement support and counselling.

We need to raise £6,150 per day to run the hospice, so every penny counts. Thank you for helping to make sure more people with a terminal illness in and around Belfast, get the care and support they need. If you would like to find out more about raising funds for our hospice, visit: https://www.mariecurie.org.uk/help/hospice-care/hospices/belfast/fundraise

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
The RNLI has been operating at full capacity since the start of lockdown. Our service has been rescuing people throughout the Coronavirus pandemic and our heroic crews commitment to saving lives has not stopped. Unfortunately, our ability to raise funds has been limited.

The average lifeboat station in the North West costs £136,000 a year to run and we are going to have a significant shortfall in income due to the Coronavirus. We are asking all our friends and communities to donate what they can to keep us running.

All along the North West coast from Silloth to West Kirby, we will always be there to keep you and your loved ones safe, on our watch, there will be no preventable deaths on the North West coast. Please help us fulfil that mission.

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
RNLI lifeboats in Scotland protect hundreds of communities with a 24-hour search and rescue service. Our volunteer crews rely on the safest, most reliable lifeboats and modern stations to launch from. 
Scotlands unrivalled coasts and waters are valued by local communities and visitors alike, with millions travelling to enjoy them, and work on them each year. But the water remains an unpredictable environment that can catch people out. People will always need our help and we will always be there to answer that call.
Keeping a modern fleet of lifeboats maintained, fuelled and ever ready to go to the rescue from all 46 of the lifeboat stations in Scotland is expensive and we rely entirely on voluntary donations to ensure this service is maintained. It costs an average of £155k to run a lifeboat station in Scotland but with the implications of Covid-19, we havent been able to fundraise as normal to help keep our lifeboats afloat. Can you help?

charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
eventName: Mercedes Benz Club RNLI Fundraising Page
story:
As members of the Mercedes-Benz Club, we are very proud of our heritage and also very proud to be supporting the Royal National Lifeboat Institution.

We attend events throughout the UK, when safe to do so, and look to raise vital funds for the Charity to help enable them to continue the running of their 24/7 emergency rescue service.

Together, we are helping to save lives at sea.

About the RNLI.

The RNLI has been operating at full capacity since the start of lockdown.

Our service has been rescuing people throughout the Coronavirus pandemic and our heroic crews commitment to saving lives has not stopped.

Unfortunately, our ability to raise funds has been limited.

The coasts of Wales and North West England are popular tourist destinations for millions of holidaymakers from the Midlands and we want to keep those coasts a safe place for everyone to visit.

The average lifeboat station in Wales, North West England and Isle of Man costs £159,000 a year to run and we are going to have a significant shortfall in income due to the Coronavirus.

We are asking all our friends and communities to donate what they can to keep us running.

When you and your loved ones visit the coast, we will always be there to keep you safe, on our watch, there will be no preventable deaths on British coasts.

Please help us fulfil that mission.

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
Everyone loves a Quiz, so why not test your knowledge and come along to our Quiz Night in support of the RNLI on Saturday 21st February.

We're holding the quiz at Vagabond's Rugby Club, Braddan, IM4 4RJ with a 7pm start time.

Tickets cost £10 per person, which includes a curry supper!

If you purchase your ticket here, please leave your name so we can help get your ticket to you.

Why the RNLI?

On the Island, the RNLI has been operating at full capacity since the start of lockdown.

Our service has been rescuing people throughout the Coronavirus pandemic and our heroic crews commitment to saving lives has not stopped.

Unfortunately, our ability to raise funds has been limited.

The average lifeboat station on the Isle of Man costs £161,000 a year to run and we are going to have a significant shortfall in income due to the Coronavirus.

We are asking all our friends and communities to donate what they can to keep us running.Our crews at Douglas, Ramsey, Peel, Port Erin and Port St. Mary will always be there to keep you and your loved ones safe, on our watch, there will be no preventable deaths on our Island.

 Please help us fulfil that mission.

For ideas on how to support or get involved please contact spencer_harris@rnli.org.uk

Your donation to this page will help support the running of stations on the Isle of Man as follows:Douglas, Ramsey, Peel, Port Erin and Port St. Mary.

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
eventName: Chertsey, Shepperton & District Branch 2021 Lifesavers Fund
story:
The RNLI Chertsey, Shepperton & District branch is supporting lifeboats in the South East that protect hundreds of communities through their 24-hour search and rescue service.

Our Crews rely on the safest, most reliable lifeboats and modern stations to launch from. From the stunning Dorset, Sussex and Kent coastlines to the unpredictable tidal Thames, our favourite places in the South east are enjoyed by millions of people from across the country every year. But the water remains an unpredictable environment that can catch people out. People will always need our help and we will always be there to answer that call.

The RNLI relies on donations from you the public to continue saving lives at sea and on the Thames. Your donation will help keep us afloat in 2021 and support saving lives for years to come.

Thank you for your support.

charity.description: Oxfam is a global movement of people who won’t live with the injustice of poverty. Together we save lives in disasters. We help people build better lives for themselves. We speak out on the big issues, like inequality and climate change. And we won’t stop until we end poverty for everyone. Join us
charity.name: Oxfam
story:
We're walking 20,000km from St Albans (UK) to Cox's Bazar (Bangladesh), visiting Oxfam projects along the way. 

We'll see the challenges communities face from conflict, to Covid-19 to the impact of the climate emergency and how Oxfam is responding to support communities to thrive, not just survive. 

With your support, Oxfam can continue its life-saving work, it can continue to put together packages of food, give farming support, set up foodbanks, support education for women and girls, and provide cash to buy essentials.

For each £15 we raise, we could help more women to understand their rights, challenge discrimination and to take up leadership roles within their local communities.

For each £35, we could help families access emergency food supplies. 

£45 could provide one of our new handwashing stations to enable frequent handwashing and disease prevention.

With your support, communities can come together to help each other.

charity.description: Oxfam is a global movement of people who won’t live with the injustice of poverty. Together we save lives in disasters. We help people build better lives for themselves. We speak out on the big issues, like inequality and climate change. And we won’t stop until we end poverty for everyone. Join us
charity.name: Oxfam
story:
Climate change is affecting millions of the worlds poorest people, right now. More frequent and extreme weather is destroying homes, and wrecking lives. The people who have done the least to cause the climate emergency are being hit the hardest, this is an injustice that can and must be stopped. Oxfam is protecting families forced to flee their homes, supporting those hit by changing weather, making sure children have a chance of a future free from poverty and responding to the deadly threat of coronavirus.

Every donation, no matter how big or small, makes a difference. Together, we won't live with poverty. Thank you in advance for the support!

charity.description: Right now, millions of children are in danger. They face violence, disease, hunger and the chaos of war and disaster. Unicef ensures more children get life-saving food, vaccinations, education and protection than anyone else. With your help, we can build a safer world for children. unicef.org.uk
charity.name: Unicef UK
story:
I am fundraising because Unicef urgently need funds to expand the scale and scope of their work supporting children affected by coronavirus, especially in countries with weaker health systems.
Just £30 could provide a full kit to protect a health-worker on the frontline, including gloves, masks and coveralls, while just £43 could help provide 1,680 pairs of disposable gloves for health workers.
The impact of a large-scale outbreak of coronavirus on children, especially poor and vulnerable children, has been immense. Children are at risk from the disease, but also from the disruption to health and education services, impacts on caregivers, and separation from family members.
Unicef has been working closely with governments and the World Health Organization (WHO) since the start of the coronavirus outbreak. Donations made to my page will help to limit the spread of the virus and reduce the impact on children and families.
title: My page to help a generation of children affected by Coronavirus
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
Name: My page to help a generation of children affected by Coronavirus

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story: I'm walking for water so others don't have to. I'm walking for the millions of women and children who walk distances every day to get the water they need for themselves and their families to survive. I'm walking to raise funds so we can make clean water normal for everyone, everywhere. Clean water is a human right that everyone, everywhere should enjoy. But around the world 1 in 10 people have no choice but to drink dirty water, often from remote sources, risking their health, their safety and their chances in life. With clean water, people have an equal chance to be healthy, educated and financially secure. Communities can thrive.
